   417→### `match`
   418→
   419→```ts
   420→match(value);
   421→```
   422→
   423→Create a `Match` object on which you can later call `.with`, `.when`, `.otherwise` and `.run`.
   424→
   857→#### `P._` wildcard
   858→
   859→The `P._` pattern will match any value. You can also use `P.any`, which is an alias to `P._`.
   860→
   861→```ts
   862→import { match, P } from 'ts-pattern';
   863→
   864→const input = 'hello';
   865→
   866→const output = match(input)
   867→  .with(P._, () => 'It will always match')
   868→  // OR
   869→  .with(P.any, () => 'It will always match')
   870→  .otherwise(() => 'This string will never be used');
   871→
   872→console.log(output);
   873→// => 'It will always match'
   874→```
   875→
  1623→### `P.infer`
  1624→
  1625→`P.infer<typeof somePattern>` lets you infer a type of value from a type of pattern.
  1626→
  1627→It's particularly useful when validating an API response.
  1628→
  1629→```ts
  1630→const postPattern = {
  1631→  title: P.string,
  1632→  content: P.string,
  1633→  stars: P.number.between(1, 5).optional(),
  1634→  author: {
  1635→    firstName: P.string,
  1636→    lastName: P.string.optional(),
  1637→    followerCount: P.number,
  1638→  },
  1639→} as const;
  1640→
  1641→type Post = P.infer<typeof postPattern>;
  1642→
  1643→// posts: Post[]
  1644→const posts = await fetch(someUrl)
  1645→  .then((res) => res.json())
  1646→  .then((res: unknown): Post[] =>
  1647→    isMatching({ data: P.array(postPattern) }, res) ? res.data : []
  1648→  );
  1649→```
